There is a [`ReadOnlyDictionary&lt;TKey,TValue&gt;`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.collections.objectmodel.readonlydictionary-2?view=netframework-4.8) class that accepts an `IDictionary&lt;TKey,TValue&gt;` dictionary in its constructor. You could just return one that wraps the `Dictionary&lt;string, Dictionary&lt;string, string&gt;&gt;`:

    public IReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, IReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, string&gt;&gt; TheDict =&gt;
        new ReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, IReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, string&gt;&gt;(_theDictionary);

A `Dictionary&lt;TKey,TValue&gt;` also implements `IReadOnlyDictionary&lt;TKey,TValue&gt;` so you can also just return the original dictionary directly unless you care about any consumer being able to cast it back to a mutable `Dictionary&lt;TKey,TValue&gt;`.

    Dictionary&lt;string, Dictionary&lt;string, string&gt;&gt; dictionary;

    var readonlyDictionary = new ReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, ReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, string&gt;&gt;(dictionary.Select(pair =&gt; new { Key = pair.Key, Value = new ReadOnlyDictionary&lt;string, string&gt;(pair.Value) }).ToDictionary(x =&gt; x.Key, x =&gt; x.Value));

If you are using .Net Core you can use `ImmutableDictionary`

    dictionary.ToImmutableDictionary(pair =&gt; pair.Key, pair =&gt; pair.Value.ToImmutableDictionary());

