You can create a [shallow copy](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/shallow-copy-and-deep-copy-in-c-sharp/) with the help of the `TypeAccessor` using something like:

	var sourceAccessor = ObjectAccessor.Create(object1);
	var targetAccessor = ObjectAccessor.Create(object2);

	var access = TypeAccessor.Create(typeof(A));
	var members = access.GetMembers();

	foreach (var member in members)
	{
		targetAccessor[member.Name] = sourceAccessor[member.Name];
	}


Have a look at the [FastMember tests](https://github.com/mgravell/fast-member/blob/master/FastMember.Tests/) for usage examples.

For a deep copy, you could check either the property name or use the [property type](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2442534/how-to-test-if-type-is-primitive) to determine whether to apply a [deep copy of lists](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14007405/how-create-a-new-deep-copy-clone-of-a-listt) or if a shallow copy is sufficient.

Edit: Here is an example for a simplified version that recursively copies properties of type `IList` (see this [question](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/794198/how-do-i-check-if-a-given-value-is-a-generic-list) on how to determine which property is a list), assuming the source and target object&#39;s lists have the same length:

    private static void MirrorObject(object object1, object object2)
    {
        var sourceAccessor = ObjectAccessor.Create(object1);
        var targetAccessor = ObjectAccessor.Create(object2);

        var access = TypeAccessor.Create(object1.GetType());
        var members = access.GetMembers();

        foreach (var member in members)
        {
            if (member.Type.IsGenericType &amp;&amp; (member.Type.GetGenericTypeDefinition() == typeof(IList&lt;&gt;)))
            {
                var list1 = (IList)sourceAccessor[member.Name];
                var list2 = (IList)targetAccessor[member.Name];
                if (list1.Count != list2.Count)
                {
                    throw new ArgumentException(&quot;Lists need to be of the same length.&quot;);
                }
                for (var i = 0; i &lt; list1.Count; ++i)
